  <h2>What is Coding?</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Coding</strong> (also called <strong>programming</strong>) is the process of writing instructions for a computer to follow. These instructions are written in special languages called <strong>programming languages</strong>. When you code, you are telling the computer exactly what to do, step by step.
  </p>
  <p>
    Everything digital was built by coding — websites, apps, video games, social media platforms, robots, and even the AI assistants on your phone. Coding is one of the most powerful skills you can learn!
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Think of coding like writing a recipe for a robot chef. The robot does exactly what you write — so you have to be precise! If you say "add 5 cups of salt" instead of sugar, it will add salt — no questions asked!
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Why Should Kids Learn to Code?</h2>
  <p>Coding isn't just for "computer people." Here's why every kid benefits from learning to code:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🧩 <strong>Problem Solving</strong> — Coding teaches you to break big problems into small, solvable steps.</li>
    <li>🎨 <strong>Creativity</strong> — You can build anything you imagine — games, apps, animations, websites!</li>
    <li>🧠 <strong>Critical Thinking</strong> — Debugging (fixing errors) trains you to think logically and carefully.</li>
    <li>💼 <strong>Career Opportunities</strong> — Tech jobs are among the highest-paying and fastest-growing careers in the world.</li>
    <li>🤝 <strong>Collaboration</strong> — Most real projects involve teams of coders working together.</li>
    <li>🌍 <strong>Change the World</strong> — Code is how you build solutions to real-world problems: apps for health, environment, education!</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How Does Coding Work?</h2>
  <p>
    Computers don't understand English or Hindi — they only understand <strong>binary</strong>: 0s and 1s (off and on signals). Programming languages bridge the gap:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>✍️ You write code in a human-readable language (like Python).</li>
    <li>🔄 A program called a <strong>compiler</strong> or <strong>interpreter</strong> translates your code into binary instructions.</li>
    <li>⚡ The computer's CPU executes those binary instructions to perform your program.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Basic Concepts Every Programmer Uses</h2>
  <p>No matter what language you learn, you'll use these core programming ideas:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>📦 <strong>Variables</strong> — Boxes that store information. Example: <code>score = 100</code> stores the number 100 in a "box" named <em>score</em>.</li>
    <li>🔁 <strong>Loops</strong> — Repeating an action many times automatically. Example: "Do this 10 times" or "Repeat until the game ends."</li>
    <li>🤔 <strong>Conditions (If/Else)</strong> — Making decisions based on whether something is true or false. Example: "If the player has 0 lives, show Game Over."</li>
    <li>🧰 <strong>Functions</strong> — Reusable chunks of code that do a specific job. Like having a "makeSandwich()" function you can call anytime!</li>
    <li>📋 <strong>Lists/Arrays</strong> — Collections of items stored together. Example: a list of all player names in a game.</li>
    <li>🐛 <strong>Debugging</strong> — Finding and fixing mistakes (bugs) in your code. Every programmer does this — all the time!</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Popular Programming Languages for Kids</h2>
  <p>There are hundreds of programming languages! Here are the best ones to start with:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🐱 <strong>Scratch</strong> — A free visual drag-and-drop language from MIT. No typing needed! Perfect for beginners aged 7+. Make games, animations, and stories. Visit <em>scratch.mit.edu</em>.</li>
    <li>🐍 <strong>Python</strong> — The most popular beginner programming language in the world. Clean, easy-to-read syntax. Used in AI, data science, web development, and automation.</li>
    <li>🌐 <strong>HTML &amp; CSS</strong> — Not strictly programming languages but essential for building websites. HTML creates the structure, CSS makes it look great.</li>
    <li>⚙️ <strong>JavaScript</strong> — Makes websites interactive. Run directly in any browser — no special software needed to get started!</li>
    <li>🎮 <strong>Lua</strong> — Used in Roblox game development. If you love playing Roblox, you can learn to BUILD games in it!</li>
    <li>🔵 <strong>Blockly</strong> — Google's visual programming language used in many educational coding platforms.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Your First Code: "Hello, World!"</h2>
  <p>
    Every programmer's first program is called <strong>"Hello, World!"</strong> — a program that simply displays the message on screen. Here's how it looks in different languages:
  </p>
  <p><strong>Python:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>print("Hello, World!")</code></pre>
  <p><strong>JavaScript:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>console.log("Hello, World!");</code></pre>
  <p><strong>HTML:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>&lt;p&gt;Hello, World!&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
  <p>
    That's it! Just one line of code to tell the computer to display a message. This is the very first step every real programmer takes!
  </p>

  <h2>Free Resources to Start Coding Today</h2>
  <p>You don't need to buy anything to start coding! Here are amazing free resources:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🐱 <strong>Scratch (scratch.mit.edu)</strong> — Visual coding for beginners. Free, fun, creative.</li>
    <li>🏆 <strong>Code.org</strong> — Amazing free coding courses for all ages. Includes Hour of Code activities.</li>
    <li>🐍 <strong>Python.org</strong> — Free Python documentation and tutorials.</li>
    <li>📺 <strong>Khan Academy (khanacademy.org)</strong> — Free programming courses in JavaScript, HTML, and more.</li>
    <li>🎮 <strong>Roblox Studio</strong> — Free game development environment where you can create Roblox games!</li>
    <li>🌐 <strong>freeCodeCamp.org</strong> — Free full-stack web development curriculum.</li>
    <li>🤖 <strong>micro:bit (microbit.org)</strong> — Code a tiny physical computer! Great for learning with hardware.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Can You Build With Code?</h2>
  <p>The possibilities are endless! Here are things real kids have built with coding:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🎮 <strong>Video Games</strong> — From simple platformers to complex RPGs.</li>
    <li>🌐 <strong>Websites</strong> — Personal blogs, portfolio sites, fan pages.</li>
    <li>📱 <strong>Mobile Apps</strong> — Useful apps that solve real problems.</li>
    <li>🤖 <strong>Robots</strong> — Programs to control LEGO Mindstorms, Arduino, or Raspberry Pi robots.</li>
    <li>🎨 <strong>Digital Art</strong> — Generative art created by code (patterns, fractals, animations).</li>
    <li>🎵 <strong>Music</strong> — Programs that create original music algorithmically.</li>
    <li>📊 <strong>Data Projects</strong> — Analysing data and creating charts or visualisations.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Programming vs Coding — What's the Difference?</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>💻 <strong>Coding</strong> — The act of writing code (the lines of instructions).</li>
    <li>🧠 <strong>Programming</strong> — The broader process: designing a solution, writing code, testing it, and debugging it.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    In everyday conversation, both words mean the same thing. A <strong>programmer</strong> = someone who writes code to build software.
  </p>

  <h2>Famous Programmers Who Changed the World</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>👩 <strong>Ada Lovelace</strong> — Often called the world's first programmer. She wrote the first algorithm in 1843!</li>
    <li>👨 <strong>Bill Gates</strong> — Co-founded Microsoft and wrote the early BASIC programming language.</li>
    <li>👩 <strong>Grace Hopper</strong> — Invented the first compiler and coined the term "debugging."</li>
    <li>👨 <strong>Linus Torvalds</strong> — Created Linux, the operating system that runs most of the world's servers.</li>
    <li>👩 <strong>Margaret Hamilton</strong> — Wrote the software that guided Apollo 11 to the Moon!</li>
    <li>👨 <strong>Mark Zuckerberg</strong> — Coded the first version of Facebook in his college dorm room.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Fun Facts About Coding</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>🤯 The average smartphone app takes between <strong>3 months and 1 year</strong> to build.</li>
    <li>🐛 The term "bug" in programming comes from a real moth found in a computer in 1947!</li>
    <li>💡 There are over <strong>700 different programming languages</strong> in existence.</li>
    <li>🌍 Google's codebase has over <strong>2 billion lines of code</strong>!</li>
    <li>👧 <strong>Zora Ball</strong> became the world's youngest app developer at age 7!</li>
  </ul>

